ğŸŒŸ Day 10 of the GFG160 Challenge ğŸŒŸ

ğŸš€ Problem Solved: Maximum Subarray Sum

ğŸ’¡ Approach Used: Kadane's Algorithm - O(n) Time, O(1) Space

âœ… Steps to Solve:
1ï¸âƒ£ Initialize Variables: Start with the first element as both maxEnding (current subarray sum) and res (maximum sum).
2ï¸âƒ£ Iterate through the Array:
     - For each element, decide whether to extend the previous subarray or start a new one.
     - Update maxEnding as max(maxEnding + arr[i], arr[i]).
3ï¸âƒ£ Track Maximum Sum: Update res if maxEnding exceeds it.
4ï¸âƒ£ Return the maximum sum (res).

ğŸ¯ Key Takeaway: Kadane's Algorithm efficiently calculates the maximum subarray sum by dynamically deciding whether to extend the current subarray or start a new one, all in a single traversal.

ğŸ’» Complexity:

Time: O(n)
Space: O(1)
ğŸ’¬ "Efficient logic meets scalable solutionsâ€”Kadane's Algorithm is a must-know!"


// C++ Program for Maximum Subarray Sum using Kadane's Algorithm

#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

// Function to find the maximum subarray sum
int maxSubarraySum(vector<int> &arr) {
    int res = arr[0];
    int maxEnding = arr[0];

    for (int i = 1; i < arr.size(); i++) {
      
        // Find the maximum sum ending at index i by either extending 
        // the maximum sum subarray ending at index i - 1 or by
        // starting a new subarray from index i
        maxEnding = max(maxEnding + arr[i], arr[i]);
      
        // Update res if maximum subarray sum ending at index i > res
        res = max(res, maxEnding);
    }
    return res;
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {2, 3, -8, 7, -1, 2, 3};
    cout << maxSubarraySum(arr);
    return 0;
}
